  "texts": [
    "We considered 9 different stimulus sequences in which a female varied her rotation, size, and position (three top traces for each stimulus sequence, see Methods for stimulus descriptions).",
    "We found that the 1-to-1 network's predictions (black traces) largely predicted the responses of the real LC neurons (color traces), despite the facts that the 1-to-1 network was never given access to neural data and that we directly read out from a single model LC unit.",
    "The average of all reported noise-corrected R 2 s here is the same as that reported in Fig. 2e.",
    "We only considered stimulus sequences for which the real LC responses reliably varied across time for the stimulus sequence.",
    "To measure this, we computed the d ′ between splits of repeats (i.e., a signal-to-noise ratio across repeats) and considered any stimulus sequence with a d ′ < 1 as unreliable, removing it from our analyses (translucent traces; see Methods)."
  ],
